Qpr was the practical capacity in the first plateau, which could be obtained from Fig. 2b. As shown in Fig. 3a, the experimental Ps(uti) was maintained at ~70% for porosity higher than 60%. Thus, at most 70% of S could be converted to Li2S4. The Li2S4 solubility in the electrolyte solvent in terms of S is Cmax = 8 M19. Assuming these Li2S4 was only dissolved into the electrolyte in the pore, its concentration would still exceed the saturation limit even at a high porosity of 70%. That means the accessible electrolyte volume was larger than Vpore. Further decrease in porosity below 60% led to a reduction of Ps(uti), since the amount of accessible electrolyte no longer fully dissolve the produced Li2S4, thus limits the utilization of active S. Therefore, we consider the first plateau will be terminated once the Li2S4 concentration reaches the saturation limit, thus the S utilization will be limited by the maximum amount of soluble Li2S4,4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
