				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p = \frac{{V\left( {{\mathrm{cat}}} \right) - V_{{\mathrm{dense}}}\left( {{\mathrm{cat}}} \right)}}{{V\left( {{\mathrm{cat}}} \right)}}$$\end{document}p=Vcat−VdensecatVcatwhere Vdense(cat) is the dense volume of the cathode (5.31 mm3) listed in Supplementary Table 1, and V(cat) is the comprehensive volume of the electrode, which is determined by the area of the cathode multiplied by the thickness of the cathode after calendaring. Therefore, the thickness of the cathode of 140, 100, 80, and 60 μm corresponds to the porosity of 70%, 60%, 50%, and 40%, respectively, for a sulfur loading of 5 mg cm−2.
